Atypical Art Deco synagogue, in the heart of the Marais; too bad it can't be visited!

This synagogue was built in 1913 by the architect Hector Guimard (1867-1942), famous for his Parisian Art Nouveau buildings. Hector Guimard, for his construction, uses reinforced concrete frames as well as hollow agglomerated stones. The benches, chandeliers, light fixtures and cast iron railings are furniture designed by Hector Guimard and are similar to the decor of the facade.

The building was created in 1913 by architect Hector Guimard, the Parisian master of Art Nouveau, for Agudas Hakehilos (אֲגֻדָּת־הַקְּהִלּוֹת, Union of Communities)[1], an association resulting from nine original Orthodox Israelite societies essentially Russian, chaired by Joseph Landau. It bears witness to the massive arrival of immigrants from Eastern Europe at the beginning of the 20th century. The construction is made of hollow agglomerated stones on reinforced concrete frames. It was officially inaugurated on June 7, 1914, but it had already been in service since October 1913.

08/2017: Apart from the place of worship, this synagogue has a particularity: that of having been designed by Hector Guimard, the famous architect known for having designed the art nouveau entrances to the Parisian metros.
